cold, zero - 30 degrees; snow deeper than usual; clear some days, foggy the last one.  Birded with Jim Lomax. Hwy 395 leading to Susanville;Mapes and Fish & Game Rd and other roads around countryside leading to Honey Lake (both Dakin and Fleming Unit) looking for AT Sparrow, No Shrike; feeders along 395  Time frame 1/11, 1/12, 1/16). Can''t split up report per day.----Per Tim Manolis: Interestingly, when kites have wintered up in that area before, they have done so in numbers.  The three previous times we had kites on the Honey Lake CBC (1976, 77 and 80) we had 3, 2, and 3 bird, respectively.  Up to 5 kites were seen up there at a time in the winter of 1977-78, but they have been very scarce in winter around Honey Lake since then (1980).

TRIP COMMENTS: Historical email to Sandy Koonce:----"Hi Sandy.  I just wanted to let you know that John--Luther, Ed Pandolfino, Cliff Hawley and I had a male--Nuttall's Woodpecker at Hesparia City Park (the one--with the fishing lake) yesterday, the 22nd.  I'm not--sure if this is an unusual location for them, but I--was surprised to see one on the east side of the--mountains.  There was also a Snow Goose there that had--taken up with the local park ducks.  It looked like it--had an injured foot.  At Silverwood Lake we had a--female Hooded Merganser, several (~5) Horned Grebes,--two Common Loons and a less-than-adult Bald Eagle.  It--looked like a third year, but I'm not positive."
